# A [[large]] [[round]] [[stone]] used for [[grind]]ing [[grain]].
#* {{quote-book|en|author=J[ohn] T[heophilus] Desaguliers|authorlink=John Theophilus Desaguliers|chapter=Lecture XII. On Engines, especially Hydrostatical and Hydraulick Machines.|title=A Course of Experimental Philosophy|location=London|publisher=Printed for W. Innys, at the West End of [[w:St Paul's Cathedral|St. Paul's]]; M. Senex, in [[w:Fleet Street|Fleet-street]]; and [[w:Thomas Longman|T[homas] Longman]], in [[w:Paternoster Row|Pater-noster-Row]]|year=1744|volume=II|page=429|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=01uStqGrc7wC&pg=PA429|oclc=915428665|passage=As it is the circular Motion of the '''Mill-ſtone''' which brings the Corn out of the Hopper by Jerks, and with a Velocity depending upon that of the Stone, other Grains are always ſucceeding, which raiſe it anew, and the Flower just made being no longer preſs'd is carry'd away into the Boulting Mill by the Circulation of Air that the '''Mill-ſtone''' puts into motion, which makes a whirling there.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Emanuel Swedenborg|authorlink=Emanuel Swedenborg|author2=[[w:John Clowes (priest)|John Clowes]], transl.|chapter=[Book of [[Revelation]],] Chapter XVIII|title=The Apocalypse, or Book of Revelations, Explained According to the Spiritual Sense; in which are Revealed the Arcana which are there Predicted, and have been hitherto Deeply Concealed: Translated into English from a Latin Posthumous Work, of the Honourable Emanuel Swedenborg [by William Hill]; and Revised by the Translator of the Arcana Cœlestia [John Clowes]|location=London|publisher=Printed and sold for the Society for Printing and Publishing the Works of the Hon. Emanuel Swedenborg, instituted in London in the year 1810; by E. Hodson, 15, Cross Street, {{w|Hatton Garden}}; sold also by T. Goyder, 8, [[w:Charles Street, Mayfair|Charles Street]], [[Westminster]]; and may be had of all booksellers in town and country|year=1815|volume=VI|page=149, paragraph 1182|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=aDE9AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA149|oclc=809571596|passage=The reason why a '''mill-stone''' signifies confirmation from the Word in both senses, is, because wheat signifies good, and fine flour the truth thereof, hence by a '''mill-stone''', by which wheat is ground into fine flour, or barley into meal, is signified the production of truth from good, or the production of what is false from evil, thus also the confirmation of truth or what is false from the Word; {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Colin Spencer|authorlink=Colin Spencer|chapter=Aquatic Ape Theory. How Early Did Fish Enter the Diet?|editor=Harlan Walker|title=Fish: Food from the Waters: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 1997|location=Totnes, Devon|publisher=Prospect Books|year=1998|page=307|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mPS0tH02IDUC&pg=PA307|isbn=978-0-907325-89-5|passage=We can tell what Australopithecines ate from the remains of their jaws and teeth. The earliest finds show teeth which are large and round like '''millstones'''&nbsp;– acting as grinding and pulverizing machines for fibrous vegetation.}}
# {{lb|en|geology}} A [[coarse]]-[[grain]]ed [[sandstone]] used for making such stones; [[millstone grit]].
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Amos Eaton|authorlink=Amos Eaton|title=Geological Text-book, for Aiding the Study of North American Geology: Being a Systematic Arrangement of Facts, Collected by the Author and His Pupils, under the Patronage of the Hon. {{w|Stephen Van Rensselaer}}|edition=2nd|location=Albany, N.Y.: Published by Websters and Skinners; New York, N.Y.: G. and C. and H. Carvill; Troy, N.Y.: William S. Parker; N. Tuttle, printer|year=1832|pages=92–93|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=uy45AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA93|oclc=63618958|passage=In North America the '''millstone''' grit, and a grey sandy and slaty rock beneath it, occur three times; and it is exceedingly difficult to distinguish these rocks in hand specimens, without the aid of organized remains. And remains are almost exclusively confined to the grey rocks. Common quarrymen, farmers, and foreign geologists, apply the names, ''greywracke'' and '''''millstone''''', to all these rocks promiscuously; neither having observed their different relative positions.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=A. H. Green|author2=C[lement] le Neve Foster|authorlink2=Clement le Neve Foster|author3=J. R. Dakyns|chapter=Lower Coal-measures or Ganister-beds|title=The Geology of the Carboniferous Limestone, Yoredale Rocks, and Millstone Grit of North Derbyshire and the Adjoining Parts of Yorkshire. (Sheets 81 N.E., 81 S.E., 72 N.E., and Adjoining Parts of 88 S.E., 82 N.W., 82 S.W., and 71 N.W. of the Map of the Geological Survey.)|series=Memoirs of the Geological Survey of England and Wales|location=London|publisher=Printed for [[w:Office of Public Sector Information|Her Majesty's Stationery Office]]; published by [[w:Longman|Longmans, Green and Co.]]|year=1869|page=11|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0jZSAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA11|oclc=970639443|passage=From the above account it will be seen how closely the '''Millstone''' Grit and the Lower Coal Measures are like one another in their lithological character. Each is a group of thick sandstones parted by shales, and in each beds of coal are very generally found on the top of the sandstones. The differences are these. Among the '''Millstones''' the sandstones are thicker, fewer, further apart, more constant both in size and character, and as a rule coarse grits or conglomerates.}}
